argin:0;">Senator <strong>Patty Murray</strong> usually flies under the rad=
ar=E2=80=94she=E2=80=99s not a
social media hyperventilator=E2=80=94relying on her considerable power as t=
he vice chair of the Senate Appropriations Committee to talk for her. So it=
 was notable that, while news cameras flocked to outraged Democrats protest=
ing <strong>Elon Musk</strong>, Murray firmly told Punchbowl that it would =
be =E2=80=9Cextremely difficult=E2=80=9D for Democrats to agree on a spendi=
ng bill when the president was =E2=80=9Cillegally blocking=E2=80=9D funding=
 approved by Congress. =E2=80=9CDemocrats and Republicans alike,=E2=80=9D s=
he warned, =E2=80=9Cmust be able to
trust that when a deal gets signed into law, it will be followed.=E2=80=9D<=
br/><br/>For those versed in Murray-ese, her commentary could be interprete=
d only as a shutdown threat. Given their margins, House Republicans can=E2=
=80=99t pass spending bills without Democratic votes unless they achieve ne=
ar <em>total unity </em>within their conference=E2=80=94a mathematical real=
ity that gives otherwise powerless Democrats their only serious leverage. I=
ndeed, Murray=E2=80=99s seemingly dry statement caught a <em>lot </em>of at=
tention
around the Hill.<br/><br/>Threatening a shutdown=E2=80=94a Republican-favor=
ed method of economic hostage-taking=E2=80=94would be a stunning shift for =
Democrats. As recently as December, Democratic aides swore to me up and dow=
n that they would never, <em>ever</em> embrace the tactic. But it=E2=80=99s=
 been a long two months=E2=80=94long enough, even, that Democrats are hinti=
ng about coming debt-ceiling negotiations, and telegraphing a possible will=
ingness to play chicken with the global economy to defend their branch=E2=
=80=99s
constitutional role from Musk.<br/><br/>Of course, when Republicans make su=
ch threats, they typically extract a few concessions, dutifully cave, and w=
ind up dealing with the opposition to pass a compromise bill. Threats, as <=
strong>Donald Trump</strong> will tell you, are just jumping-off points to =
start negotiations. (See: tariffs.) But there are reasons to take Murray mo=
re seriously than the more prolific blusterers of the Senate. She=E2=80=99s=
 the most senior Democratic senator, at the peak of her
powers. She=E2=80=99s a close ally of minority leader <strong>Chuck Schumer=
</strong>, and she=E2=80=99s not known to go rogue. When Murray speaks, it =
should be assumed the entire caucus is behind her. She is, moreover, one De=
mocrat that Republicans actually listen to. And whatever the fate of spendi=
ng negotiations in March, she has crystallized how Democrats see their disp=
ute with Musk: as a war for Congress=E2=80=99s very survival as an independ=
ent branch of government.</p></div>
